    <h3>Shaping the Client's Experience</h3>
    <p>A million versions of experience exist - accordingly, different expectations of what makes a good experience; thus, experience programs are often rendered ineffective and un-measurable because of this basic conflict of perspective. What does it even mean? Take, for example, the annual client appreciation event, both laborious and anticipated as a touchpoint for your clients. Is planning and running that event the responsibility of the Client Experience (“CX”) team? Do you have a CX team? How does it coordinate with other experiences? Do clients feel like your organization delivers a cohesive experience, or is it all over the map?</p>
